<font color="#FF0000">VIETNAM: THE HAUNTING WAR.</font><br>
<tt>Thu Dec 12 14:45:32 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
<br>
Although I was not alive during the Vietnam war I have studied it deeply due to personal ties.  My father is a Vietnam Vet and I have seen the post war trauma in effect now for 23 years.  <br><br>
The description of this war as haunting is a very good one.  It is one I know I can't even let go.  I think it has this haunting effect due to the extreme conflict of opinion from day one on whether or not we should have been involved.  My grandfather was in WWII.  He wasn't even 18 and he lied about his age so he could join the Merchant Marines.  It was honorable to be a soldier or to even aide in any way in that war.   It was patriotic.  Though it was frightening to send young men off to war at that time parents were proud to do so.  <br><br>
Vietnam is a completely different story.  There was no respect for the war, so there was no respect for those fighting it.  The effects that can have on an individual, let alone a nation is devastating.  I can't imagine being trained to fight, kill the enemy, follow orders, do your duty, stay alive, just to find out when you return from battle that the war has just begun.  The 'enemy' that the soldier killed was in vain, the time spent in the jungle trying to stay alive was in vain, and upon returning no one is thanking you for serving your country.  Instead people are calling you names.<br><br>
When my father finished his tour, he went from the jungle one day to driving a plow  and farming the next.  Nothing was said.  He was supposed to forget it even happened.  There are still ghosts because when the soldiers came home they were expected to put Vietnam in the closet and lock the door.  The survival techniques they learned in the jungle were now being used on the farm.  Dodging finger pointing and blame.  <br><br>
A large mistake that was made was blaming the war on the soldiers when they came home.  They didn't start it ...they just fought it.  
